# Problem:
# rules_pkg's pkg_rpm rule builds RPMs by running make_rpm, which is a
# py_binary. When rules_python compiles this py_binary, it generates a bootstrap
# wrapper script with a hardcoded shebang: "#!/usr/bin/env python3". When the
# kernel executes this script, it looks for python3 on the system PATH. If
# Python is not installed locally, the action fails immediately with
# "/usr/bin/env: 'python3': No such file or directory", before the wrapper ever
# gets a chance to locate the hermetic Python interpreter.
#
# What this flag does:
# By default, rules_python uses bootstrap_impl=system_python, which generates a
# Python bootstrap script (hence the "#!/usr/bin/env python3" shebang — it
# needs a Python interpreter just to start). Setting bootstrap_impl=script tells
# rules_python to generate a shell bootstrap script instead. Shell (/bin/sh) is
# universally available, so the shebang works everywhere.
#
# Why it solves the problem:
# The shell-based bootstrap script can directly locate and exec the hermetic
# Python interpreter from the runfiles tree without needing any Python on the
# system to get started.
build --@rules_python//python/config_settings:bootstrap_impl=script
